{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_ekalaka_ver01/data/sn86075298/00517178573/1930122501/0840.xml":{"full_text":"FUND ALLOINENT\nMADE BY BOARD\nState Educational Body Lays Plana\nFor Distributing Bond Money\nFor Building Purposes\nAt a meeting of the state board of\neducation at Helena the past week a\ndecision was reached by that body to\nrecommend to the Montana legisla\nture which convenes in January ap\npropriation aggregating $2,355,000 for\nthe six units of the greater university\nand the four other institutions under\nthe board\u2019s direction.\nOther state institutions, Governor\nErickson told the board, request the\nfollowing amonuts for buildings:\nPenitentiary, $300,000; hospital,\n$200,000; sanitarium, $200,000; sol\ndiers\u2019 home, $15,000.\nThe combined requests amount to\n$3,070,000 which in excess of the bond\nissue voted at the last election.\nThe board will make the following\nrecommendations for appropriations\nfor structures and repairs at institu\nions it supervises:\nNorthern Montana school at Havre,\n$500,000 for administration and in\nstruction building, residence hall for\nwomen and heating plant. Eastern\nMontana Normal school at Billings,\n$600,000 for a main building with\n30 classrooms and a teachers\u2019 training\nschool, physical education plant, aud\nitorium and library and repairs.\nState college at Bozeman, $390,000\nfor a residence for women, an insti\ntutional management house, a new\nservice shop, a steam and forge shop,\nnew structures at the experiment sta\ntion, veterinary building for research\nwork and repairs to Hamilton hall,\nwomen\u2019s dormitory. State university\nat Missoula, $435,000 for journalism\nand pharmacy buildings and repairs.\nSchool of mines at Butte, SIOO,OOO\nfor reconstruction of the main build\ning, improvement of campus, installa\ntion of library stacks and repairs to\nthe heating and ventilating system.\nNormal college at Dillon, SIOO,OOO\nfor improvement of residence halls,\nrepairs to other buildings and addi\ntional work on the physical education\nplant. School for deaf and blind at\nBoulder, $50,000 for repairs. Indust\nrial school at Miles City, SBO,OOO for\nnew cottages. Orphans\u2019 home at Twin\nBridges, SIOO,OOO for repairs to a\nbuilding condemned by the state fire\nmarshal.\nNORTHERN PACIFIC\nWINS SKIRMISH\nFollowing the closing of a hear\ning by the Interstate Commerce com\nmission at Glendive on the petition\nof the Northern Pacific to build a 24\nmile line from Woodrow to near\nBloomfield in Dawson county, it was\nannounced by Examiner Haggerty\nwho heard the testimony that he would\nrecommend to the commission that the\nNorthern Pacific be granted the right\nto construct the branch. Haggerty\nsaid he based his decision on the be\nlief the proposed extension is neces\nsary to permit further development\nof the rich Bloomfield region. He\nalso said he believed the Northern\nPacific deserves traffic return on its\nsusstained development program of\nthe last 25 years.\nSTATE BRIEFS\nHelena.\u2014Richland county has pre\nsented for payment its $85,000 issue\nof bridge bonds recently purchased\nby the state board of land commission\ners. The money will be matched with\nfederal aid funds for construction of\na 1,231-foot bridge across the Yellow\nstone river near Sidney. I. M. Brand\njord, commissioner of state lands and\ninvestments, issued an order for pay\nment of the bonds.\n....Lewistown.\u2014Oscar Stephens, called\nthe most successful stockman who\never operated in central Montana, fore\ncast his own weather, says Judge Roy\nE. Ayers, who, in youthful days, was\nknown as Stephen\u2019 \"Kid Cowboy.\u2019\u2019\nStephens, the judge says, based his\nplans for the winter on the weather\nof the first three days of December.\nThe weather on December 1 meant\nto him similar weather during Jan\nuary. December 2 represented Feb\nruary, and December 3, March.\nThe plan never failed for \u201cSpud\u201d\nEtephens, the judge says.\nBozeman. \u2014The Billings Gas com\npany Monday started making arrange\nments for piping natural gas to Boze\nman.\nThe firm, together with the Mon\ntana Power company, was granted a\nfranchise here recently.\nWilliam M. Holland, president of\nthe Billings company and general\nmanager of the Ohio Oil company,\nhas arrived with a draftsman to se\ncure plats of the city.\nHolland said the pipe line to this\ncity would be laid early next spring.\nHelena.\u2014Receipts from the metal\nmines gross tax on 1929 production\nin Montana totaled $550,295,55, accor\ning to J. H. Stewart, chairman of the\nstate board of equalization.\nOf that amonut the Anaconda Cop\nper Mining company paid $504,119.75.\nThe Butte Superior company paid\n$28,169.33, the St Joseph Lead com\npany, $11,055, and the East Butte\nCopper company, $6,633.68.\nTh* mine* tax assessed in 1929 ex\nceeded tha 1928 total by 8186,757.24.\nHalf of the income goes to the\nstate general fund and the other half\nto the school equalisation board.\nBILLINGS STOCK SHOW\nLARGEST IH THE STATE\nTo Offer Great Opportunity For\nBreeders to Acquire the\nFinest of Animals\nThe sixth Annual Show and Sale\nof the Yellowstone Registered Live\nstock Association to be held in Bil\nlings on January 6, 7 and 8 will be the\nlargest combination sale of Herefords\nand Shorthorns in the state. A total\nof 227 are entered. Among these are\n70 Horned Herefors, 29 Polled Here\nfords, 99 Shorthorns, and four milk\ning Shorthorns and 25 4-H fat steers.\nThe Billings Sale offers a wonderful\nopportunity for Montana ranchers and\nlivestock men to purchase pure bred\nsires and breeding stock and is ex\nceptional from the standpoint of the\nnumber of bulls offered for sale. Of\nthe total number of breeding animals\n179 are bulls and 23 are females.\nProminent breeders from all parts of\nthe state have made consignments to\nthis year\u2019s sale which is the largest\never held in Billings.\nLouis Vinke, head of the animal\nhusbandry department at the Montana\nState college and Dick Richards, live\nstock specialist of the Montana Ex\ntension Service have been engaged to\njudge the show. The program for\nthe three days will be; Tuesday, Jan\nuary 6, judging of all stock; Wed\nnesday, January 7, sale of 4-H fat\nsteers followed by the sale of Short\nhorns; January 8, Thursday, sale of\nHerefords.\nCatalogs and bills are now avail\nable for those who are interested. All\nrequests should be addressed to R. B.\nMcKee, secretary of the Yellowstone\nRegistered Livestock Association, Bil\nlings, Montana.\nThe following is the list of breeders\nwho have consigned to the January\nsale:\nHerefords: C. F. Kinmonth, Bal\nlantine; W. H. Donald, Melville; Henry\nStole, Big Timber; Burch Halla\nday, Choteau; Ralph Selkirk, Fish\ntail; Belle Curtis Wright, Stevens\nville; George B. Sim, Highwood; W.\nH. Coop, Huntley; Sim Schock,\nHighwood; Lester Thompson, Boze\nman; L. Chatterton, Geyser; Thomas\nH. Watson, Hobson; Art Lever, Bil\nlings.\nPolled Herefords: E. S. Blodgette,\nBillings; Taylor Ranch Co., Sanford;\nWilliam Spidel, Roundup; J. M. Dan\nforth, Rapelje; Arthur Patterson,\nGlendive.\nShorthorns: Elmer Johnson, Liv\ningston; Harry Tesell, Manhattan; B.\nE. Nutting, Laurel; A. J. Goyins,\nStanford; Hoschke Ilros. Grove,\nBuffalo; Hoschke Bros, and Fair\nbanks, Buffalo; Sales Son, Galla\ntin Gateway; Gray J. Keene, Town\nsend; B. B. White, Billings; A. P.\nCormier, Billings; Dick Decock, Hy\nsham; William Robinson, Red Lodge;\nOtto Oswald, Broadview; F. C. Metz\nger, Rothiemay; J. M. Rook, Red\nLodge; Grace Blodgette, Billings;\nEmil Borberg, Billings; C. E. Axtell,\nBozeman; A. W. Bonney, Red Lodge;\nGeorge W. Spring Son, Belgrade.\nMilking Shorthorns: H. A. Kientiz,\nBridger; Chas.*T. Simpson, Bridger;\nW. S. Bryan, Hardin; C. E. McKitt\nrick, Billings.\nFARM LOCALS\nForsyth.\u2014A total of 817,650 was\nsaved to Rosebud county stockmen on\n181 cars of feed shipped in and on\nlivestock shipped out to feed during\nthe 60 days the emergency freight\ntariff was in effect.\nHavre.\u2014Preparations for entertain\nment of the members of the Montana\nDairy Products Manufacturing associ\nation are under way. The annual con\nvention will be held here January 12\nand 13.\nSpeakers who have accepted invi\ntations include E. B. Duncan, devel\nopment agent of the Great Northern\nrailway; H. B. Brooks, secretary of\nthe Montana crimme commission and\neditor of the Havre Daily News and\nChinook Opinion; Fred Traber of\nGreat Falls, creameryman and presi\ndent of the association; Glen Sands,\ndairy expert at Montana State college,\nand B. F. Thrailkill, chief of the dairy\ndivision of the state department of\nagriculture.\nHelena.\u2014At the annual showing of\nthe International Grain and Hay show\nheld at Chicago in connection with the\nInternational Livestock exposition\nNovember 29-December 6, Montana\nagain proved itself the outstanding\nstato in the grain and hay division,\nits exhibitors winning more awards\nthan those of any other state or Ca\nnadian province.\nIn this division Montana captured\nthree world\u2019s shammpionships, those\nfor barley and field beans, and in the\nlivestock division it won the award\nfor champion carload of feeder cattle.\nAside from these sweepstakes\nawards Montana exhibitors won 134\nplaces in the two shows, of which 28\nwere first premiums.\nHelena.\u2014A decline of only about\nfour points in Montana ranges dur\ning November is revealed in the peri\nodical report of the state-federal crop\nreporting service.\nThe condition of cattle and sheep\nwas unchanged during the month,\nthe statement says.\nFeeding has been carried on since\nabout the middle of November in the\nsections where ranges are inacces\nsible.\nLate fall and winter range feed is\nreported to be about 80 per cent of\nnormal, with the lowest supplies in\nthe southeastern quarter of the state.\nThe Ronan Pioneer, December 25, 1930\nOUR COMIC SECTION\nI Events in the Lives of Little Men J\n\nGnHW PIP a |7jr 'LI 1\nB f, k Nr\nf V\n_ I\n[th 11 ha I IF r H u\nI J I -ML JLx\nI Bfe\u00df XX -A\nw. n.-u> I.-\u2019\nFINNEY OF THE FORCE The Dummy\n/MS CABBAGE-\nI /ah' WE MOP DOES WE\n--^TCICKt-\nWSThRi\nl /J\n\n\u2019/I/ I A 1 K\nH 'till I il! I I\n1 i a!?\u2122* S? r\n\\pOMES NATURAL-LIKE I J\nTHE FEATHERHEADS Shoo, Felix! Shod!\nWERE HAUIN A LITTLE J WERE PUTTIN' HARBY,,\n/RALLY TO NIGHT; FELIX- WANT 4 HARRY ^l/BACK IH OFFC&.EKBCN?\nMOO TO MEET SOME OF lUE I FOQ QOl \u201cFELIX HERE IS GONTA\nBOYS WE RE PUTTIN\u2019 IN OFFICE! nIiGUBOU-\nFINE BUNCH OF FELLAS DO I <l-^ HOOO.EH FELIX?\nSOME GOOD SOME TiME/ !_ _\n\u201cM/a -vl\nof .mHHC \u2014vEy-|r aJ-t\nJ\nP AN' YET MOO PRO&LY\nSPENT TWICE THAT MUCH/ r Z J\nV ALREADY ONMxJR Hn fol' H~\nX CAMPAIGN^ JU 1 L\u201d!\na TO\nThis Week I\n4r Arthur Brisbane\nImportant Questions\nProhibition Illegal!\nSewod in a Bear Skin\nStrange Motions\nLet those that torment themselves\nwith foolish fears, and permit their\nfears to interfere with business and\nthe return of prosperity, ask them\nselves these questions:\nHave we not had depressions be\nfore? Did we not then think that the\nend of the world was coming? Did\nnot men go about shaking their heads,\nsaying:\n\u201cYes, but this Is a different kind of\ndepression; we never had anything\nlike this.\u201d\nThose that have been tn business\na reasonable length of time recall the\nhead-shaking, moaning and groaning\nof 1907.\nHaven't there been good times since\n1907? Didn't business \"pick up,\u201d to\nput it mildly, after 1907? Haven't we\nsince then added hundreds of billions\nto the country\u2019s wealth?\nAnd haven't we got everything now\nthat we ever had?\nCould anything be more stupid than\ntalk and action of a kind harmful to\nbusiness, to banks and other Institu\ntions upon which the prosperity of us\nall and every num's employment de\npend absolutely?\nThe country discusses the decision\nof Federal Judge William T. Clark,\nwho says that prohibition isn't legal i\nbecause the people didn't pass on it.\nJudge Clark is interesting to mil\nlions of men and women, although\nthey may not know it, for he is one\nof the famous O. N. T. Clark thread\nfamily.\nJudge Clark's decision that pro\nhibition Isn't legal will be reversed\nby Hie Supreme court, probably.\nEverything Is comparative, even sor\nrow. The head of a great bank In\nNew York tells of a client \u201cwith the\nsaddest face I have ever seen tn my\nlife.\u201d\nOne year ago this client was worth\nat least sixty millions of dollars. And\ntoday his fortune is reduced to not\nmore than twenty million dollars.\n\u201cAnd you can\u2019t Imagine,\u201d said the\nbunker, \u201chow that man suffers.\u201d\nIvan the Terrible, czar of Russia,\nto subdue those that opposed him, in\nvented queer punishments.\nOn one occasion he had a bishop\nsewed up In a bear skin, and the bish\nop, In his bear skin, thrown to a pack)\nof half-starved dogs.\nThe bishop suffered horribly, of\ncourse, but only for a few minutes.\nHis total suffering amounted to far.\nless than the sufferings of some that\nhave seen their fortunes and the re\nsults of their life work gradually tak\nen from them, bit by bit, during the\npast year.\nHarvard sends reassuring news'\nabout this grand old earth, on which\nmen have lived, according to Profes\nsor Osborne, for forty million years,\nand on which geologists, physicists, as\ntronomers, tell us we shall continue\nto live for at least a million million\nyears more.\nOur strange rolling domicile Is one'\nwith many motions. We all know that\nit turns around on Its axis, rolls\naround the sun in 365 days, and is\ntraveling through space accompany\ning the sun on its journey. But\nmost of us forget about the many\nother motions of the earth.\nWe are glad to learn from Harvard\nthat a \u201crecent mysterious shaking of\nthe earth's crust was a movement back\nand forth, rhythmical and regular, six\nseconds to each swing.\"\nAnd while the earth\u2019s crust does\nmove, it moves only two ten-thou\nsandths of an inch in either direction,\nthe motion continuing for many days.\nWo should be very grateful that lit\ntle human microbes can be safe on\nthis whirling globe, twenty-five thou\nsand miles around, ns heavy as though\nit were made of solid steel, with hot\nlire under our feet, and absolute zero,\nmore than 400 degrees below freezing,\nall around us.\nMr. Cutter, president of the United\nFruit company, says that we did a\nbusiness last year with Latin-America\nof-more than two thousand million dol\nlars, whereas we ought to be doing a\nbusiness of ten thousand million\ndollars.\nTn Ilie Caribbean countries, says\nSir. Cutter, we reach fewer than 20\nper cent of the possible customers.\nAmerican business men, with the\nDepartment of Commerce leading,\nshould look Into that ten billion dollar\npossibility. We need the business.\nFrance has banking troubles and\ndeals with doubtful bankers In a dras\ntic fashion. Thirty-five French bank\ners ate in jail, and 185 under govern\nment Investigation.\nGermany has found a wny to make\ndanger signals plain even for the color\nblind. Drivers approaching a railroad\ntrack need not know the difference be\ntween white and red. The warning\ncomes tn flashes. While the way Is\nclear a white light flushes forty times\na minute. When a train approaches\na red light Is turned on and flashes\neighty times to the minute.\nThe train automatically switches the\nred and white lights on and off.\n1\u00bb1\u00ab. br Kins rutur** Svadtost*. taat","height":"23820","width":"16564"}}
